Template: send-to-influx/sources-to-configure
Type: multiselect
Choices: hue, zappi, harvi, eddi, octopus, openmeteo, carbonintensity, speedtest, nuki
Default:
Description: Which data sources do you want to configure now?
 You can leave this empty and edit /etc/send-to-influx/settings.yaml by hand
 later, or run 'dpkg-reconfigure send-to-influx' at any time to change this.
 Only the fields needed to actually reach each source's API are asked here -
 tuning settings (intervals, timeouts, which fields to collect) keep their
 shipped defaults and can be adjusted in settings.yaml afterwards.

Template: send-to-influx/influx-url
Type: string
Default:
Description: InfluxDB URL (leave blank for a local instance)
 The base URL of your InfluxDB server, e.g. https://influx.example.com:8086.
 Leave this blank to default to http://localhost:8086.
 When reconfiguring an install whose InfluxDB credentials are already stored
 in systemd-creds, a blank URL keeps the currently configured one - enter
 http://localhost:8086 explicitly to point it back at a local instance.

Template: send-to-influx/influx-identity
Type: string
Default:
Description: InfluxDB user (v1) or organisation (v2)
 For InfluxDB v1 (username/password authentication) enter the username. For
 InfluxDB v2 (token authentication) enter the organisation name. Which one
 applies is detected automatically once the server is reachable - you don't
 need to know your InfluxDB version to answer this.
 When reconfiguring, leaving this blank keeps the currently configured value.

Template: send-to-influx/influx-secret
Type: password
Description: InfluxDB password (v1) or API token (v2)
 For InfluxDB v1 enter the password. For InfluxDB v2 enter the API token.
 When reconfiguring, leaving this blank keeps the credential already stored
 in systemd-creds, if any (a secret kept in plaintext in settings.yaml is
 not read back here).

Template: send-to-influx/mqtt-broker-host
Type: string
Default:
Description: MQTT broker hostname or IP address
 Needed by MQTT-based sources (currently Nuki). The broker (e.g. Mosquitto)
 must be on your LAN - see the README's "Nuki Smart Lock (MQTT)" section for
 first-time broker setup, including provisioning the lock itself.
 When reconfiguring, your previous answer is offered as the default - this
 field is required, so accept or edit it rather than blanking it.

Template: send-to-influx/mqtt-username
Type: string
Default:
Description: MQTT broker username for send-to-influx
 send-to-influx's own (read-only) broker login - use a separate account from
 the one the lock itself publishes with, so either can be rotated or revoked
 independently.
 Leave blank (with the password also blank) if your broker allows anonymous
 access - that is a valid configuration, not an incomplete one.
 When reconfiguring, a blank answer keeps the currently configured value -
 switching an existing authenticated install to anonymous is done by blanking
 mqtt.username in settings.yaml and running
 'send-to-influx-set-credential mqtt-password --remove', not via these
 prompts (blank means keep, never remove - the same convention as every
 other credential here).

Template: send-to-influx/mqtt-password
Type: password
Description: MQTT broker password for send-to-influx
 The password for the broker username above. Leave blank (with the username
 also blank) for anonymous access, if your broker allows it.
 When reconfiguring, leaving this blank keeps the credential already stored
 in systemd-creds, if any (a secret kept in plaintext in settings.yaml is
 not read back here).

Template: send-to-influx/mcp-enable
Type: boolean
Default: false
Description: Enable the remote MCP server (for an MCP client such as Claude)?
 Lets an MCP client (e.g. Claude Desktop or Mobile) query your collected device
 history, and optionally control your devices, over an OAuth-protected HTTPS
 endpoint. The server binds a private interface only (127.0.0.1:8420) - you must
 front it with your own TLS-terminating reverse proxy. Leave this off unless you
 want that; the collector works exactly as before either way.

Template: send-to-influx/mcp-public-url
Type: string
Default:
Description: External HTTPS URL your reverse proxy serves for the MCP server
 e.g. https://mcp.example.org - the address you'll add as a connector in your
 MCP client (e.g. Claude). Required to enable the server (its OAuth metadata must
 advertise it);
 must start with https://. When reconfiguring, your previous answer is offered
 as the default - accept or edit it rather than blanking it (like the MQTT
 broker host, it's a required field, so a blank one leaves the server
 unconfigured; to rotate only the password, leave this and the username as
 pre-filled and enter just the new password below).

Template: send-to-influx/mcp-user
Type: string
Default:
Description: MCP server login username
 The username for the OAuth login page that gates access to the MCP server.
 When reconfiguring, your previous answer is offered as the default - accept
 or edit it rather than blanking it (a blank username leaves the server
 unconfigured).

Template: send-to-influx/mcp-password
Type: password
Description: MCP server login password
 The password for the MCP login username above.
 When reconfiguring, leaving this blank keeps the credential already stored
 in systemd-creds, if any (a secret kept in plaintext in settings.yaml is
 not read back here).

Template: send-to-influx/hue-host
Type: string
Default:
Description: Hue bridge hostname or IP address

Template: send-to-influx/hue-user
Type: password
Description: Hue bridge username/API key
 See https://developers.meethue.com/develop/get-started-2/ for how to
 generate this.
 When reconfiguring, leaving this blank keeps the credential already stored
 in systemd-creds, if any (a secret kept in plaintext in settings.yaml is
 not read back here).

Template: send-to-influx/hue-temperature-units
Type: select
Choices: C, F
Default: C
Description: Temperature units for Hue sensor readings
 Pre-filled from your system locale where possible, but always worth
 double-checking.

Template: send-to-influx/myenergi-apikey
Type: password
Description: MyEnergi API key
 Shared across Zappi/Eddi/Harvi devices - asked once regardless of how many
 of those you selected.
 When reconfiguring, leaving this blank keeps the credential already stored
 in systemd-creds, if any (a secret kept in plaintext in settings.yaml is
 not read back here).

Template: send-to-influx/zappi-serial
Type: string
Default:
Description: Zappi device serial number

Template: send-to-influx/harvi-serial
Type: string
Default:
Description: Harvi device serial number

Template: send-to-influx/eddi-serial
Type: string
Default:
Description: Eddi device serial number

Template: send-to-influx/octopus-api-key
Type: password
Description: Octopus Energy API key
 From https://octopus.energy/dashboard/developer/
 When reconfiguring, leaving this blank keeps the credential already stored
 in systemd-creds, if any (a secret kept in plaintext in settings.yaml is
 not read back here).

Template: send-to-influx/octopus-mpan
Type: string
Default:
Description: Octopus Energy electricity meter MPAN
 The 13-digit MPAN number found on your bill.

Template: send-to-influx/octopus-meter-serial
Type: string
Default:
Description: Octopus Energy electricity meter serial number
 Found on your bill or on the meter itself.

Template: send-to-influx/openmeteo-latitude
Type: string
Default:
Description: Latitude for Open-Meteo weather data

Template: send-to-influx/openmeteo-longitude
Type: string
Default:
Description: Longitude for Open-Meteo weather data
